(137, 1, 285, 2418, '<p>Also known as Ayudha Puja and Astra Puja, Saraswathi Pooja is observed on the 9th day of the Navaratri festival that occurs on days between September to October. During the evening of Mahanavami, the Goddess of wisdom, art, and literature is revered by keeping the books, instruments, and tools are kept for Puja in front of the idol of Goddess Saraswati (in the Golu/Kolu display) and this remains untouched until the next day &ndash; Vijayadasami day. Tools that are used in day-to-day activities including ploughs, spanners, hammers, and machines like computers and laptops are kept for Puja. People also wash their vehicles and perform puja for them.</p>\r\n<p>As per mythology, it is believed that the weapons used by Chamundeshwari to kill Mahishasur have been kept for worship. Another story goes as one of the five brothers of Pandava, Arjuna on Vijayadashami Day, had retrieved his weapons from the Shami tree, where he had placed them before going to exile for 13 years.</p>\r\n<p>This day is considered auspicious to start learning or for Vidyarambham. Small children enter the world of knowledge on this day by writing for the first time, either by a priest or elders of the family. The Maha Saraswathi Amman temple in Thiruvarur is the only temple dedicated to Goddess Saraswathi in Tamil Nadu. On Vijayadashami day, parents bring their young children and they make them write for the very first time inside the temple. Special pujas are also performed on this day.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1),
(138, 1, 286, 2426, '<p>Chithirai Festival in Madurai celebrates the celestial union of Lord Sunderswarar (Lord Shiva) and Goddess Meenakshi, considered to be Lord Vishnu&rsquo;s sister. The festival also known as Chithirai Thiruvizha, Meenakshi Thirukalyanam or Meenakshi Kalyanam falls at the beginning of April or the Tamil month Chithirai. It is a 15 days celebration that brings harmony to everyone irrespective of caste and religion. The festival also sees a union between the two Hindu sects, Shaivites and Vaishnavites, devotees of Shiva and Vishnu respectively. Around one-million people including tourists come to witness the event that takes place in Madurai, South Tamil Nadu&rsquo;s biggest temple. The festival is one of India&rsquo;s oldest temples commences by hoisting a flag (Kodi Yetram).</p>\r\n<p>The last days of the festivals are celebrated in Kallazhagar temple, in the Alagar Hills in Madurai. Lord Kallazhagar is considered to be Goddess Meenakshi&rsquo;s brother, an incarnation of Lord Vishnu. Legend says that Goddess Meenakshi who was born out of the fire was the charming and brave Queen of Pandya Kingdom. She grew into a successful warrior. On her visit to Mount Kailas, the abode of Lord Shiva, she realised that she was the incarnation of Goddess Shakthi and Shiva promised that he would come down to Madurai to tie the knot. When the ceremony happened, Lord Kallazhangar could not witness it. He gave his offerings to his sister near the river Vaigai. A three-course meal is provided to the devotes after the Sundershwar-Meenakshi wedding is recreated. Lord Kalalzhagar reaches the Vaigai river on a golden horse.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The chariot that runs through the streets of Madurai is a delight to the eyes of natives as well as tourists. It is believed that the ruler of Pandya kingdom, along with his wife (Sundareshwar and Meenakshi) come in the chariot to visit their subjects. Putting aside the religious aspects, the festival also draws visitors for its wide display of exhibitions, and performance of cultural shows, entertainment programmes. There will be huge play areas with giant wheels. Dress materials and accessories like glass bangles will be displayed in the 16th-century monument Puthu Mandapam near the temple. One can also excite their taste buds with different varieties of snacks and drinks at the pandal or marquee erected on the roadside.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1),
(139, 1, 287, 2434, '<p>Immortalized in countless Indian movies are the soaring pine woods, awe-inspiring landscapes and pleasant atmosphere of the Pine Tree Forests of Ooty. These woodlands overlooking the majestic view of Sandynulla Lake, are an ideal honeymoon destination. The air scented with pine cones, the rich silence of Nature and the spectacle of dancing butterflies are just a few of the magical elements in these enchanted woods.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Nestled in the slopes of Nilgiris, the Pine Tree Forest is a grove of orderly growing pine trees that are several hundreds of years old. These ancient woods are home to a wide variety of fauna, ranging from fluttering butterflies that delight the air to wild goats that roam the woods. Wander with your beloved through these woods obscured in white blanket of mist or enjoy a leisurely picnic with family, Pine Tree Forest promises a fairy-tale-like experience to all visitors.</p>\r\n<p>One of the key attractions of the woods that lures visitors is the picturesque landscape that the Pine Tree Forest offers as a backdrop for photography and video shooting. Tourists visit the woods to capture and immortalise&nbsp; important events in their life against the scenery made popular by countless movies. Another feature of Pine Tree Forest is an opportunity it gives you to test your horse-riding skills. Riding on a horse along the slopes of the hill with wind in your hair is guaranteed to give you a shot of thrill and adventure. The Pine Tree Forest has camping facilities also. The woods overlooking the majestic view of the Nilgiris make for an ideal location to set a camp with your family or friends, to watch the mist rolling on and off the slopes and to gaze at the stars through the pinewoods at night.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1),
(140, 1, 288, 2450, '<p>The Lake Park, as the name suggests, is located on the banks of the Ooty Lake. It is the perfect place to laze around and spend a leisurely day in, and is located in the city centre just opposite the railway station and very near the bus terminus.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The exotic garden here displays wide swathes of flower beds filled with vibrant seasonal flowers. The reclaimed lake used to be part of the garden in 1977, which was funded by the Tourism Department under Hill Area Development Programme. The highlight of the park is the illumination of different hues of light during dark hours. The fibreglass dome here was constructed in 1978. There are dinosaur statues and entertaining games to occupy the kids.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1),
(141, 1, 289, 2466, '<p>Spread over 22 acres in Udhagamandalam town is another tranquil spot near&nbsp; the Ooty Lake, that is home to a vast number of deer. About six acres of the lake have been used to develop the park.&nbsp; The park was inaugurated in 1986 and is maintained by the Tamil Nadu Forest Department. Although the name suggests that the park is exclusively for deer, the Deer Park is also home to a wide variety of birds and rabbits. This is one of the high-altitude animal parks in India and is easily accessible by road.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The Sambar and Chital species of deer can be found in the park. The Deer Park in Ooty is a haven for Nature lovers as it is wrapped in a chilly climate and surrounded by enticing flora and fauna.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1),
(142, 1, 290, 2482, '<p>The Government Museum in Ooty, situated on the Ooty-Mysore Road, gives a peek into the culture and ancient heritage of the tribes of Ooty. The Museum is also known as the Stone house or the Kal bungalow by the locals.</p>\r\n<p>The ecological facts about the district, taxidermy artefacts, the arts and crafts of Tamil Nadu are displayed here. There are separate rooms dedicated to geological items, musical instruments and ancient statues. There is an impressive collection of tribal objects that gives a glimpse of the culture and society of the tribes of Ooty. Ooty is home to almost 18 tribes &ndash; the Toda tribe being the most popular. The Toda tribe is a pastoral community. An extensive collection of the craft, sculptures, houses, jewellery, clothing style and farming implements used by the tribespeople are displayed here along with the ecological details of the region.</p>\r\n<p>The Museum is open on all days except Fridays and second Saturdays.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1),
(143, 1, 291, 2498, '<p style=\"text-align: left;\">One of the major industrial, commercial and cultural centres in India, Chennai is the capital city of Tamil Nadu. A city of great history and heritage, Chennai is today one of the most visited cities in the world. Originally called Madras, Chennai is located along the Coromandel Coast in the Bay of Bengal and is a major port city in the region.&nbsp;<br /><br />Chennai is often referred to as the Detroit of India because of the presence of a thriving automobile sector. Chennai is also home to many major industries that add significantly to the financial growth of India. Lately Chennai has also risen in ranks as one of the most promising IT destinations in India. Once the capital of South Indian cinema, today Chennai is home to the Tamil Film industry that has viewers all over the world.&nbsp;<br /><br />However, Chennai is much more than high rises and Hi-tech IT parks. The city boasts of various scenic spots and celebratory ambiances that make the place a preferred travel location for tourists from across the world. The Koovam river flows through the heart of Chennai and the Adyar River through the South. Being a coastal destination, Chennai is blessed with many picturesque beaches as well. All these offer a traveller stunning views to cherish for a lifetime. The real beauty of Chennai lies in its intrinsic traditional traits. Referred to as the cultural capital of the South, Chennai enthrals the visitors with its distinctive architecture, music, art, heritage, monuments and warm hospitality. So if you are looking to visit a destination that offers a multisensory tour experience, then Chennai is the place to be in.</p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1),
